instruction: What propels vomit out of your stomach?
output_1: The muscles in the wall of your stomach contract and push the contents up through your esophagus. Your stomach is located lower than your esophagus and there is a valve at the lower end of your esophagus. When the muscles in your stomach contract, the valve at the lower end of your esophagus opens and the contents of your stomach move up through the valve into your esophagus. The contents of your stomach are acidic and the valve at the lower end of your esophagus is designed to protect you from the acid. This is why you feel the urge to vomit when your stomach is empty and why you vomit up acid if you eat something that is too acidic. The muscles in your stomach wall are controlled by nerve cells in the brain. There are special nerve cells in your brain called motoneurons that are connected to these stomach muscles. When these nerve cells fire, the stomach muscles contract. The signal that fires these nerve cells is called a nerve impulse. Nerve impulses travel down your spinal cord and from your spinal cord down your nerve roots to your muscles. This is how your stomach muscles are able to contract and push the contents of your stomach up through your esophagus.
output_2: Vomit is propelled out of your stomach by gravity. As your stomach empties, the pressure inside decreases and it becomes less dense, causing it to move down towards your esophagus.

instruction: How do noise cancelling headphones/earphones work?
output_1:
Noise canceling headphones and earphones use microphones that pick up ambient noise and an electronic circuit that cancels the noise, resulting in a quieter listening experience. The microphone is usually located at one of the earpieces, so the ambient noise is picked up from the same direction as the sound that is being reproduced by the headphones or earphones. The noise is then amplified and inverted, producing a sound wave that has the same amplitude, but the opposite phase. This sound wave cancels out the sound that is being picked up by the microphone, reducing the perceived noise.

Some noise canceling headphones and earphones also have active noise cancellation, which means that the electronic circuit can adjust the amount of noise cancellation depending on the ambient noise. This allows the headphones to automatically adjust to different listening environments.

The main disadvantage of noise canceling headphones and earphones is that they require a constant power supply from a battery or a USB cable. This can limit the amount of time that the headphones can be used before needing to be charged. Additionally, noise canceling headphones and earphones can reduce the sound quality of the audio that is being played through them. For example, some noises that are not meant to be heard by the listener, such as airplane engines, can be masked by the noise cancellation circuitry.
output_2:
Noise-canceling headphones work by using two microphones, one in each earphone. One microphone detects external noise such as traffic, airplane engines, etc. and the other microphone detects the noise generated by the music player or media device. The signal from the external noise is inverted and added to the audio signal from the media device. The result is a canceling signal that is output through the headphones. This signal suppresses or cancels out the external noise, leaving only the desired audio signal from the media device.

Source: http://www.head-fi.org/t/724649/nois...

instruction: Write a short story based on the following prompt:  You find an abandoned puppy hiding from the rain on your doorstep. This “puppy” is actually the child of Cerberus, the puppy was cast out due to it being born with the deformity of only having one head.

I found an abandoned puppy hiding from the rain on my doorstep.
“Oh dear, what happened?” I thought to myself.
“I’m sorry, I don’t have a lot of time for this. I’ll call the pound”
I dialed the number of my local animal shelter and told the person on the other line what had happened.
“Okay, thanks, we’ll be on our way to pick it up” the receptionist said.
A couple of hours later, a man in a suit and a woman in a lab coat showed up to my house with a big box.
“Hi” said the man in the suit. “We’re here to pick up the puppy.”
“Puppy?” I asked.
“I’m sorry, the person on the phone told us that you had a puppy on your doorstep. We have one here in the box that we would like to give you.”
“Oh, right, I did have a puppy. He’s actually just around here somewhere”
I ran out of the house and started looking around for him.
“Where could he be?” I thought to myself.
I looked all around the yard but I couldn’t find him.
“He’s probably hiding in the bushes.”
I walked around the bushes and found him laying there on the ground.
“Are you okay?” I asked.
“Yeah” he answered. “What are you going to do to me?”
“I’m not sure” I said. “Do you want to go to the pound?”
“No” he said. “I want to go home with you”
“Well, the person on the phone said that we couldn’t keep it”
“Do you have a dog house?” I asked.
“No” he said.
“How about some food?” I asked.
“No” he said.
“What about a bowl?”
“Yeah, I have a bowl”
“Okay, let me get you some food”
I went inside the house and found a bag of dog food in the pantry.
I came back outside and gave him the food.
“Thank you” he said.
“Here, let me help you up” I said.
I grabbed the puppy and started to walk him to the car.
“Where are we going?” he asked.
“To your new home” I said.
“You’re not taking me to the pound are you?”
“No” I said. “I promised that I would keep you”

instruction: Why do most plastics turn white when you bend them?
output_1:
There are several reasons why most plastics turn white when you bend them:

1. If you are bending a hard plastic like ABS, it is very likely that you are stressing the molecular bonds in the plastic, and the bonds are breaking. This causes the molecules to line up with the force acting on them, and the plastic gets opaque white. This is known as "stress whitening".

2. If you are bending a flexible plastic like TPE (Thermoplastic Elastomer), it is likely that you are stressing the molecular bonds in the plastic, and the bonds are breaking. The molecules are not aligning, but the plastic is still able to stretch to accommodate the force acting on it. This is known as "viscoelastic relaxation". The molecules then re-align and return to a less stretched configuration as the force is released. As a result of this process, the plastic turns opaque white. This is known as "stress whitening".

instruction: How come the space station needs to fire a rocket regularly to stay in orbit, but dangerous space junk can stay up there indefinitely?
output_1:
The space station is in geostationary orbit. This means that it remains in the same place relative to the Earth's surface, but the planet rotates underneath it.

The station is actually orbiting the Earth twice a day. It also orbits the sun, so it also makes a complete orbit twice a day.

The rocket is fired at the right time so that it keeps the station in the same position relative to the surface of the planet. The station must also have some form of engine to keep itself from falling back towards the planet.

Objects that are just floating around are not in any kind of orbit. They are moving relative to each other, but there is no planet or star pulling on them. They don't have any reason to move in a certain direction.
output_2:
The space station is in an orbit with a very precise altitude and angle. To stay in that orbit, it needs to continuously fire its engines.
 Space junk has a much more random orbit. While it might sometimes come very close to the space station, it will never hit it, because it has too much randomness.

instruction: In the US, onions are the only commodity that can not be traded as a futures contract due to 1958 Onion Futures Act. Why was this restriction not repealed along with other deregulation measures of 80s and 90s? Why was onion seen as different from other commodities?
output_1:
The 1958 Onion Futures Act was passed to reduce price manipulation in the commodities market, especially during periods of shortages. The law restricts the trading of futures on onions, along with a few other agricultural products. The law was initially passed to prevent price manipulation by large, commercial interests. The act has not been repealed because the law was passed with the intention of protecting the interests of small, local farmers. Large commercial interests would not be affected by the restriction, and may argue that the law is no longer necessary. On the other hand, small, local farmers may see the law as a barrier to growth. The restriction is no longer relevant in the current context, where prices in the commodities market are mostly controlled by large commercial interests. It may be necessary to repeal the restriction to allow for free trade in the commodities market.

instruction: What are some 21th century's philosophical problems?
output_1:
*   The philosophy of language: The philosophy of language has been heavily affected by developments in the sciences and technology, and especially by the rise of linguistics. In particular, it has been affected by the rise of cognitive science. These developments have led to a move away from the traditional distinction between semantics and pragmatics. This has also led to a more interdisciplinary approach to the philosophy of language.
*   The philosophy of mind: The philosophy of mind has been heavily affected by developments in neuroscience and cognitive science. This has led to a move away from the traditional dualism between the mind and the body, and towards a more holistic view of the mind as being intimately connected to the brain.
*   The philosophy of action: The philosophy of action has been heavily affected by developments in psychology, neuroscience, and economics. This has led to a move away from the traditional view of the agent as a unitary entity, and towards a more sociocultural understanding of the agent as being embedded in a social and physical environment.
*   The philosophy of ethics: The philosophy of ethics has been heavily affected by developments in psychology, neuroscience, and economics. This has led to a move away from the traditional view of ethics as being rooted in religious or metaphysical notions, and towards a more empirical and scientific understanding of ethics.
*   The philosophy of religion: The philosophy of religion has been heavily affected by developments in the sciences and technology, and especially by the rise of the scientific method. This has led to a move away from the traditional view of religion as being based on belief in supernatural entities, and towards a more scientific understanding of religion as being rooted in human cognition and culture.
*   The philosophy of value: The philosophy of value has been heavily affected by developments in psychology, economics, and neuroscience. This has led to a move away from the traditional view of value as being rooted in metaphysics, and towards a more scientific understanding of value as being rooted in human cognition and culture.
output_2:
In philosophy, the problems of contemporary philosophy are often associated with metaphysics, which deals with the nature of existence. Contemporary philosophy of mind concerns issues such as the nature of the mind and consciousness, the problem of mental causation, and the nature of perception and reasoning. Contemporary philosophy of science investigates issues related to the foundations of science, such as the nature of scientific explanation and the relationship between theory and observation. Contemporary philosophy of language examines the nature of language and communication, including questions about the mind-independent nature of language, the nature of meaning, and the role of context in communication. Contemporary philosophy of action concerns the nature of action, agency, and responsibility.

The problems of contemporary philosophy are also associated with ethics, which concerns the nature of right and wrong, and with social and political philosophy, which deals with fundamental issues of justice and equality. Contemporary philosophical problems also include questions related to religion, such as the relationship between religion and science, the nature of religious belief, and the role of religion in society.

instruction: How do remote tribes that have no new genetic material for thousands of years not die out because of inbreeding?
output_1:
Remote tribes with no new genetic material for thousands of years are known as isolated populations. Isolated populations are vulnerable to inbreeding. Inbreeding is a form of genetic hitchhiking in which individuals with deleterious mutations that are harmful at low frequency in a population can become concentrated in the gene pool of a small population, leading to higher frequencies of the mutations.

One example of this is the Icelandic population. After the Vikings settled Iceland in the 9th century, they imported only a handful of people from Norway. Over the centuries, they mated with native Icelandic women, creating an isolated population of Vikings. In the early 2000s, a study of the Icelandic population found that many of them had inherited a harmful mutation in the MC1R gene that is associated with red hair.

Another example is the Amish. The Amish are a conservative Christian sect that lives a simple life in America. Over the centuries, they have not adopted many modern technologies and practices. Their lifestyle has isolated them from the wider world, and they are an example of an isolated population. In the 2000s, researchers sequenced the genomes of 21 Amish and found that they had many harmful mutations that are associated with diseases and developmental disorders.

The fact that these remote tribes have not died out despite thousands of years of inbreeding is evidence that humans are able to adapt to their environment by evolving over time.

output_1:
In high school years back they told me the appendix was useless. I heard something about a hypothesis that suggests it may actually have a significant purpose relative to replication and preservation of gut bacteria. What's that about?

What do we know about how gut bacteria works?

* There are more than 10 times as many bacterial cells in the human body than there are human cells.
* Bacteria make up about 3.8 pounds (1.7 kg) of a typical person’s body weight.
* Bacteria in the gut help digest food and absorb nutrients. They also help protect against infection and may play a role in preventing certain chronic diseases.
* Bacteria help make vitamins and other essential nutrients that the body needs. They also help prevent the growth of harmful bacteria.
* A healthy gut microbiome plays an important role in digestive and immune function, and may help protect against obesity, diabetes, and other conditions.
* The gut microbiome plays a crucial role in health and disease, and its study is emerging as one of the most exciting areas of research.

It is typically about 6 inches (15 centimeters) long and contains a hollow, spiral organ called the "appendix vermiformis".  The exact function of the appendix is unknown, but it is thought to play a critical role in protection against infection and in the development of healthy gut bacteria.

It also seems to play an important role in regulating metabolism, mood, and many other aspects of overall health. The gut microbiota also seems to influence the risk of certain diseases, including diabetes, inflammatory bowel disease, and certain types of cancer.  

The gut microbiota seems to exert its effects through multiple different mechanisms, including by altering the expression of genes in the host gut cells, the production of various metabolites, and the activation of the host immune system.

instruction: why are elementary particles structureless?

  * Particles are observed in a process called scattering. When a particle collides with another particle, the colliding particles may change their velocity but they will not change their structure. So if you have a particle with structure, when it collides with another particle, the structure will change. But since the structure is changing, you can't use the information of the particle's original structure to predict the particle's new structure. So in this case, you can only predict what will happen if the structure does not change, which is that the particle will remain structureless.

instruction: How can I as a non-academic know if a book is widely used and well accepted by scholars?
output_1:
Here are some ways you can determine if a book is widely used and well accepted by scholars:

1. Review the reviews. Search for reviews of the book on Amazon, Goodreads, and other online book review sites. Read the reviews and see what people are saying about it. Look for comments about how well-researched the book is, how readable it is, and how useful the information is.
2. Check the author’s reputation. Look up the author’s name and see what other works they have written. Search for reviews of those books to see if they are well-received by other scholars. Check to see if the author has a website or blog where they discuss their work.
3. Look for citations in other scholarly works. Search for the book’s title or the author’s name in online databases like Google Scholar, JSTOR, and the library catalog. Look for citations to the book in other scholarly works. If there are a lot of citations to the book, it means that other scholars are using it as a source in their own research.
4. Talk to your librarian. Ask your librarian for suggestions about how you can tell if a book is well-received by other scholars. Your librarian may be able to recommend databases or other tools that will help you find information about the book.

instruction: What is the best explanation of Newton’s laws?
output_1:
Newton’s first law states that “A body at rest will remain at rest, and a body in motion will remain in motion unless acted upon by a force”.
Newton’s second law states that “For every action there is an equal and opposite reaction”.
And Newton’s third law states that “For every action, there is a reaction and it is always in the opposite direction”.
output_2: Newton's laws are a set of three physical laws named after Sir Isaac Newton.  They describe the relationship between the force on a particle, the particle's mass, and its acceleration.  These laws have been enormously influential in physics and are used to describe the motion of objects in the real world as well as in the mathematical world of physics.

instruction: I'm buying a car for the first time, any advice?
output_1:
Here is some advice for buying a car for the first time:
1. Start with a list of the features you absolutely need and features you want but don't need.
2. Search for cars online on multiple websites and in person at dealerships.
3. Once you've found some cars you like, try to test drive them.
4. Talk to a car salesperson at the dealerships. They can tell you about the car's condition and history.
5. Check if the car has any recalls. If it does, ask the dealership to fix it for free.
6. Talk to a mechanic who can give you a car inspection.
7. Read online reviews about the car and dealerships.
output_2: You need to think about how you'll use the car, and how much you can afford to spend. You also need to do some research, because cars are complicated! If you’re buying a new car, you should shop around to see which dealers have the best prices, and you might want to wait for a sale. If you’re buying used, you should check carfax.com to see if the car has any history of accidents or major repairs.  You should also take a test drive, and make sure everything works as it should, and that you like the way the car drives.
